Title: The Tell-Tale Heart
Credit: Written by
Author: Edgar Allan Poe
Source: Adapted from book
Draft date: 3/21/2026
Notes: Gothic period live-action, mid-19th century. Dim candlelight, deep shadows, one continuous oppressive house. NARRATOR is a thin pale man of about thirty-five, dark hollow eyes, trembling hands, dark waistcoat over white shirtsleeves; hair disheveled. OLD MAN is frail, white-haired, in a nightshirt; his left eye is pale blue with a milky film—the vulture eye. Three police officers in dark period coats and hats.

FADE IN:

INT. NARRATOR'S CHAMBER - NIGHT

Close on NARRATOR's face—sweating, eyes wide, speaking straight to us with forced calm. A single candle gutters beside him. The old house creaks.

NARRATOR
True!—nervous—very, very dreadfully nervous I had been and am; but why will you say that I am mad? The disease had sharpened my senses—not destroyed—not dulled them. Above all was the sense of hearing acute. I heard all things in the heaven and in the earth. I heard many things in hell. How, then, am I mad? Hearken! and observe how healthily—how calmly I can tell you the whole story.

He leans closer. A floorboard groans somewhere beyond the wall.

NARRATOR (CONT'D)
It is impossible to say how first the idea entered my brain; but once conceived, it haunted me day and night. Object there was none. Passion there was none. I loved the old man. He had never wronged me. He had never given me insult. For his gold I had no desire. I think it was his eye! yes, it was this!

INT. OLD MAN'S BEDROOM - DAY

The OLD MAN sits by a shuttered window in thin daylight. He turns. His pale blue vulture eye—filmed, dead-looking—catches the light and holds on NARRATOR in the doorway.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
He had the eye of a vulture—a pale blue eye, with a film over it. Whenever it fell upon me, my blood ran cold.

NARRATOR's hand tightens on the doorframe. He forces a gentle smile.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
And so by degrees—very gradually—I made up my mind to take the life of the old man, and thus rid myself of the eye forever.

INT. HALLWAY OUTSIDE OLD MAN'S BEDROOM - NIGHT

Midnight. NARRATOR stands at the closed door with a dark lantern, all shut. He moves with exaggerated care—wise, cunning, proud.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
Now this is the point. You fancy me mad. Madmen know nothing. But you should have seen me. You should have seen how wisely I proceeded—with what caution—with what foresight—with what dissimulation I went to work! I was never kinder to the old man than during the whole week before I killed him.

He turns the latch—oh, so gently—and opens the door a crack.

INT. OLD MAN'S BEDROOM - NIGHT

Pitch dark. Shutters fastened. NARRATOR eases the door wider and thrusts in the closed lantern, then his head—slowly, very slowly.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
And every night, about midnight, I turned the latch of his door and opened it—oh, so gently! It took me an hour to place my whole head within the opening so far that I could see him as he lay upon his bed. Ha!—would a madman have been so wise as this?

He undoes the lantern a hair. A single thin ray slides across the bedclothes and finds the OLD MAN's face—asleep, the vulture eye closed.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
And this I did for seven long nights—every night just at midnight—but I found the eye always closed; and so it was impossible to do the work; for it was not the old man who vexed me, but his Evil Eye.

INT. OLD MAN'S BEDROOM - DAY

Morning. NARRATOR throws open the shutters, hearty and bright. The OLD MAN blinks awake. NARRATOR speaks courageously, smiling.

NARRATOR
And how have you passed the night, eh? Well? Well?

The OLD MAN nods, unsuspecting. NARRATOR clasps his shoulder with false warmth.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
So you see he would have been a very profound old man, indeed, to suspect that every night, just at twelve, I looked in upon him while he slept.

INT. HALLWAY OUTSIDE OLD MAN'S BEDROOM - NIGHT

The eighth night. NARRATOR at the door again, lantern in hand. His face shines with triumph. He opens the door little by little—slower than a watch's minute hand.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
Upon the eighth night I was more than usually cautious in opening the door. Never before that night had I felt the extent of my own powers—of my sagacity. I could scarcely contain my feelings of triumph.

A soft chuckle escapes him.

Within: a sudden stir of bedclothes.

INT. OLD MAN'S BEDROOM - NIGHT

Black as pitch. NARRATOR's head is in. His thumb slips on the tin fastening of the lantern.

A sharp metallic click.

The OLD MAN springs up in bed.

OLD MAN
Who's there?

NARRATOR freezes in the opening—does not move a muscle. Silence stretches.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
I kept quite still and said nothing. For a whole hour I did not move a muscle, and in the meantime I did not hear him lie down. He was still sitting up in the bed listening;—just as I have done, night after night, hearkening to the death watches in the wall.

The OLD MAN remains upright, staring into darkness. A slight groan—low, stifled, the sound of mortal terror.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
Presently I heard a slight groan, and I knew it was the groan of mortal terror. I knew the sound well. I knew what the old man felt, and pitied him, although I chuckled at heart.

On the OLD MAN: eyes wide in the dark, whispering to himself.

OLD MAN
(whispered)
It is nothing but the wind in the chimney—it is only a mouse crossing the floor... It is merely a cricket which has made a single chirp.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
Yes, he had been trying to comfort himself with these suppositions: but he had found all in vain. Death, in approaching him, had stalked with his black shadow before him, and enveloped the victim.

NARRATOR, still patient, opens a very little crevice in the lantern. A single dim ray, like the thread of a spider, shoots out and falls full upon the vulture eye.

It is open—wide, wide open.

NARRATOR's face contorts with fury as he stares at the dull blue eye and its hideous veil.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
I saw it with perfect distinctness—all a dull blue, with a hideous veil over it that chilled the very marrow in my bones; but I could see nothing else of the old man's face or person: for I had directed the ray as if by instinct, precisely upon the damned spot.

A low, dull, quick sound begins—like a watch enveloped in cotton. The beating of the OLD MAN's heart. It grows quicker, louder.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
I knew that sound well, too. It was the beating of the old man's heart. It increased my fury, as the beating of a drum stimulates the soldier into courage.

NARRATOR holds still, scarcely breathing, the ray fixed on the eye. The heartbeat pounds louder—louder.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
Meantime the hellish tattoo of the heart increased. It grew quicker and quicker, and louder and louder every instant. And now at the dead hour of the night, amid the dreadful silence of that old house, so strange a noise as this excited me to uncontrollable terror. I thought the heart must burst. And now a new anxiety seized me—the sound would be heard by a neighbour! The old man's hour had come!

With a loud yell NARRATOR throws open the lantern and leaps into the room.

The OLD MAN shrieks once—once only.

NARRATOR drags him to the floor and pulls the heavy bed over him. NARRATOR stands above, smiling gaily.

Beneath the bed: the heart still beats, muffled. Then—silence.

NARRATOR heaves the bed aside. Kneels. Places his hand upon the OLD MAN's heart. Holds it there.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
Yes, he was stone, stone dead. There was no pulsation. He was stone dead. His eye would trouble me no more.

INT. OLD MAN'S BEDROOM - NIGHT (LATER)

Candlelight. NARRATOR works hastily but in silence. He dismembers the corpse—head, arms, legs—methodical, wary. A tub stands ready; it catches all. No stain reaches the floor.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
If still you think me mad, you will think so no longer when I describe the wise precautions I took for the concealment of the body. First of all I dismembered the corpse. I cut off the head and the arms and the legs.

He pries up three planks from the flooring, deposits the remains between the scantlings, and replaces the boards so cleverly that the floor looks untouched.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
I then replaced the boards so cleverly, so cunningly, that no human eye—not even his—could have detected any thing wrong. There was nothing to wash out—no stain of any kind—no blood-spot whatever. I had been too wary for that. A tub had caught all—ha! ha!

A distant bell tolls four.

INT. STREET DOOR - NIGHT

Still dark as midnight. A knocking at the street door.

NARRATOR goes down with a light heart and opens it.

Three men enter: FIRST OFFICER, SECOND OFFICER, and THIRD OFFICER—dark coats, calm faces, perfect suavity.

FIRST OFFICER
A shriek was heard by a neighbour during the night. Suspicion of foul play has been aroused. We are officers of the police—deputed to search the premises.

NARRATOR smiles—what has he now to fear?—and bows them in.

NARRATOR
Gentlemen, welcome. The shriek was my own—in a dream. The old man is absent in the country. Search—search well. I bid you.

INT. WHOLE HOUSE - NIGHT

NARRATOR leads them through rooms, candle held high, manner easy. They look; he urges them on.

INT. OLD MAN'S BEDROOM - NIGHT

NARRATOR shows them the OLD MAN's treasures—secure, undisturbed. In the enthusiasm of his confidence he brings chairs in.

NARRATOR
Rest from your fatigues, gentlemen. Sit. Sit.

He places his own seat upon the very spot beneath which the corpse is hidden. Sits. Smiles.

The officers sit. They are satisfied. They chat of familiar things. NARRATOR answers cheerily.

Then—his face pales. He touches his temple. A faint ringing.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
Ere long, I felt myself getting pale and wished them gone. My head ached, and I fancied a ringing in my ears: but still they sat and still chatted. The ringing became more distinct—until, at length, I found that the noise was not within my ears.

The low, dull, quick sound returns—a watch enveloped in cotton. The heartbeat. NARRATOR gasps. The officers hear it not; they smile and talk on.

NARRATOR talks more freely, more fluently, voice heightening.

NARRATOR
Yes—yes, as I say—the neighborhood is quiet—very quiet—

The sound increases. He rises, argues about trifles in a high key, violent gesticulations.

NARRATOR (CONT'D)
—and the weather! Have you remarked the weather? Trifles—mere trifles—

He paces the floor with heavy strides. Foams. Raves. Swings his chair and grates it upon the boards—but the noise rises over all.

Louder—louder—louder.

The officers chat pleasantly and smile.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
Was it possible they heard not? Almighty God!—no, no! They heard!—they suspected!—they knew!—they were making a mockery of my horror! I could bear those hypocritical smiles no longer! I felt that I must scream or die! and now—again!—hark! louder! louder! louder! louder!

NARRATOR shrieks, pointing at the floor beneath his chair.

NARRATOR
Villains! Dissemble no more! I admit the deed!—tear up the planks!—here, here!—It is the beating of his hideous heart!

The officers spring up. NARRATOR still points, broken, at the boards as the sound pounds on.

FADE OUT.

THE END
